97
00:09:30,796 --> 00:09:34,125
Advanced Reasoning & Multi-Step Problem Solving.

98
00:09:34,125 --> 00:09:47,610
The biggest under-appreciated development in AI over the past year has been the emergence of genuine reasoning capabilities—not just pattern matching on training data, but the ability to work through novel problems step by step.

99
00:09:47,610 --> 00:09:56,937
Chain-of-Thought (CoT) Reasoning: The foundational technique involves prompting the model to "think step by step" rather than jumping directly to an answer.

100
00:09:56,937 --> 00:10:02,514
This simple change dramatically improves performance on complex reasoning tasks.

101
00:10:02,514 --> 00:10:12,046
O1 and O3 Reasoning Models: OpenAI's "o1" series (and the more powerful "o3" variants) represent a paradigm shift.

102
00:10:12,046 --> 00:10:18,259
These models don't just generate text—they engage in extended internal reasoning before responding.

103
00:10:18,259 --> 00:10:26,276
The model might "think" for 30 seconds to several minutes on a difficult problem, exploring multiple approaches before settling on an answer.

104
00:10:26,276 --> 00:10:33,452
The results are remarkable: O3 achieved silver medal performance on the International Mathematical Olympiad.

105
00:10:33,452 --> 00:10:38,103
O1 scores in the 99th percentile on competitive programming problems.

106
00:10:38,103 --> 00:10:42,839
Complex logic puzzles that stump GPT-4 are solved reliably.

107
00:10:42,839 --> 00:10:51,577
Extended Thinking in Claude: Anthropic's Claude 3.5 Sonnet includes "extended thinking" capabilities in API mode.

108
00:10:51,577 --> 00:10:59,413
You can allocate additional compute budget for complex reasoning tasks, allowing the model to work through problems more thoroughly.

109
00:10:59,413 --> 00:11:03,223
When to Use Reasoning Models: Mathematical problem solving.

110
00:11:03,223 --> 00:11:04,774
Complex code debugging.

111
00:11:04,774 --> 00:11:07,683
Strategic analysis with multiple variables.

112
00:11:07,683 --> 00:11:10,267
Legal or regulatory interpretation.

113
00:11:10,267 --> 00:11:12,947
Scientific hypothesis evaluation.

114
00:11:12,947 --> 00:11:16,517
When Standard Models Are Better: Simple text generation.

115
00:11:16,517 --> 00:11:17,598
Translation.

116
00:11:17,598 --> 00:11:18,752
Summarization.

117
00:11:18,752 --> 00:11:21,613
Tasks where speed matters more than depth.

118
00:11:21,613 --> 00:11:24,377
High-volume, low-complexity queries.

119
00:11:24,377 --> 00:11:26,841
Autonomous Agents & Tool Use.

120
00:11:26,841 --> 00:11:36,949
The concept of "AI agents" has been heavily hyped, but beneath the marketing noise lies genuine capability that's transforming how software is built.

121
00:11:36,949 --> 00:11:49,377
What Agents Actually Are: An AI agent is an LLM connected to tools (functions, APIs, databases) with the ability to plan multi-step actions and execute them autonomously.

122
00:11:49,377 --> 00:11:53,993
Unlike a chatbot that responds to individual queries, an agent can:

123
00:11:53,993 --> 00:11:55,471
Receive a high-level goal.

124
00:11:55,471 --> 00:11:57,478
Break it down into sub-tasks.

125
00:11:57,478 --> 00:12:00,014
Select and use appropriate tools.

126
00:12:00,014 --> 00:12:02,202
Handle errors and adjust plans.

127
00:12:02,202 --> 00:12:05,074
Complete the goal with minimal human intervention.

128
00:12:05,074 --> 00:12:15,231
Function Calling Explained: Modern LLMs support "function calling" (also called "tool use")—the ability to generate structured outputs that invoke external code.

129
00:12:15,231 --> 00:12:25,062
MCP (Model Context Protocol) - The Game Changer: Anthropic's Model Context Protocol standardizes how LLMs interact with external systems.

130
00:12:25,062 --> 00:12:33,211
Think of it as a "USB standard for AI"—any MCP-compatible tool can plug into any MCP-compatible LLM.

131
00:12:33,211 --> 00:12:39,714
MCP enables: Seamless integration with databases, APIs, and file systems.

132
00:12:39,714 --> 00:12:43,031
Secure, sandboxed execution environments.

133
00:12:43,031 --> 00:12:46,216
Standardized error handling and retry logic.

134
00:12:46,216 --> 00:12:50,459
Cross-model compatibility (write once, use with any LLM).

135
00:12:50,459 --> 00:12:59,582
Computer Use Capabilities: Anthropic's Claude can directly control a computer—clicking buttons, filling forms, navigating applications.

136
00:12:59,582 --> 00:13:02,839
This isn't science fiction; it's deployed capability.

137
00:13:02,882 --> 00:13:08,144
Use cases: Automating repetitive workflows in legacy applications.

138
00:13:08,144 --> 00:13:10,776
QA testing of web applications.

139
00:13:10,776 --> 00:13:13,649
Data entry from unstructured sources.

140
00:13:13,649 --> 00:13:19,947
Navigating government portals (particularly useful in India where many services lack APIs).

141
00:13:19,947 --> 00:13:25,800
Production vs Demo Reality: Here's the honest truth about agents in 2026:

142
00:13:25,800 --> 00:13:30,223
Demos: Show agents completing complex tasks flawlessly.

143
00:13:30,223 --> 00:13:36,437
Production: Requires extensive error handling, human oversight, and fallback strategies.

144
00:13:36,437 --> 00:13:39,430
The gap is narrowing but remains significant.

145
00:13:39,430 --> 00:13:44,190
Successful production agents typically: Have clearly bounded domains.

146
00:13:44,190 --> 00:13:48,336
Include human-in-the-loop checkpoints for critical decisions.

147
00:13:48,336 --> 00:13:51,810
Implement robust retry and recovery logic.

148
00:13:51,810 --> 00:13:54,118
Log everything for debugging and audit.

149
00:13:54,118 --> 00:13:58,168
Multi-Modal Understanding (Vision + Text + Audio).

150
00:13:58,168 --> 00:14:00,800
Modern LLMs aren't limited to text.

151
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:04,731
They can see, hear, and reason across modalities.

152
00:14:04,731 --> 00:14:10,392
Beyond "Describe This Image": Vision capabilities have matured far beyond image captioning.

153
00:14:10,392 --> 00:14:11,762
Today's models can:

154
00:14:11,762 --> 00:14:15,259
Extract structured data from complex documents.

155
00:14:15,259 --> 00:14:19,082
Understand charts, graphs, and technical diagrams.

156
00:14:19,082 --> 00:14:22,026
Read handwritten text (including Hindi script).

157
00:14:22,026 --> 00:14:25,452
Analyze UI designs and suggest improvements.

158
00:14:25,452 --> 00:14:29,719
Identify objects, count items, and reason spatially.

159
00:14:29,719 --> 00:14:36,305
Document Processing: This is where vision capabilities become transformative for Indian businesses.

160
00:14:36,305 --> 00:14:42,050
Indian Government Document Understanding: The ability to process documents like: Aadhaar cards.

161
00:14:42,050 --> 00:14:43,132
PAN cards.

162
00:14:43,132 --> 00:14:44,586
Voter IDs.

163
00:14:44,586 --> 00:14:45,812
Bank statements.

164
00:14:45,812 --> 00:14:47,279
Property documents.

165
00:14:47,279 --> 00:14:48,348
Court orders.

166
00:14:48,348 --> 00:14:56,858
This is transformative for fintech, legal tech, and govtech applications where document processing has traditionally required manual data entry.

167
00:14:56,858 --> 00:15:04,839
Video and Audio Analysis: Video understanding: Frame-by-frame analysis, action recognition, temporal reasoning.

168
00:15:04,839 --> 00:15:09,875
Audio transcription: Near-human accuracy in English, improving in Hindi.

169
00:15:09,875 --> 00:15:15,596
Real-time processing: Gemini 2.0 supports streaming video analysis.

170
00:15:15,596 --> 00:15:18,457
Real Scientific Research Contributions.

171
00:15:18,457 --> 00:15:24,791
AI isn't just a productivity tool—it's making genuine contributions to scientific discovery.

172
00:15:24,791 --> 00:15:32,531
AlphaFold and Protein Structure Prediction: DeepMind's AlphaFold has predicted the structure of nearly every known protein.

173
00:15:32,531 --> 00:15:37,062
This isn't incremental improvement; it's a paradigm shift in biology.

174
00:15:37,062 --> 00:15:43,072
Tasks that previously required years of experimental work can now be accomplished in hours.

175
00:15:43,072 --> 00:15:48,865
Impact on India: Indian pharmaceutical companies use AlphaFold predictions for drug design.

176
00:15:48,865 --> 00:15:54,094
Academic research at IITs and CSIR labs has accelerated dramatically.

177
00:15:54,094 --> 00:15:58,913
Biotech startups can compete globally with lower capital requirements.

178
00:15:58,913 --> 00:16:06,305
Drug Discovery Acceleration: AI is now integral to drug discovery pipelines: Target identification.

179
00:16:06,305 --> 00:16:07,543
Molecular design.

180
00:16:07,543 --> 00:16:09,154
Toxicity prediction.

181
00:16:09,154 --> 00:16:11,317
Clinical trial optimization.

182
00:16:11,317 --> 00:16:16,257
Several AI-discovered drugs are now in clinical trials globally.

183
00:16:16,257 --> 00:16:28,661
Mathematical Theorem Proving: AlphaProof and AlphaGeometry represent breakthroughs in AI mathematical reasoning: AlphaProof solved problems from the International Mathematical Olympiad.

184
00:16:28,661 --> 00:16:33,396
AlphaGeometry solved geometry problems at IMO gold-medal level.

185
00:16:33,396 --> 00:16:38,168
These systems discover novel proofs, not just verify existing ones.

186
00:16:38,168 --> 00:16:46,053
Materials Science: AI accelerates discovery of new materials: Battery materials with higher energy density.

187
00:16:46,053 --> 00:16:47,952
Superconductor candidates.

188
00:16:47,952 --> 00:16:50,764
Catalysts for clean energy reactions.

189
00:16:50,764 --> 00:16:57,663
Climate Modeling: AI improves climate predictions and enables: Higher-resolution weather forecasting.

190
00:16:57,663 --> 00:17:02,014
Better extreme event prediction (critical for India's monsoon planning).

191
00:17:02,014 --> 00:17:04,190
Carbon capture optimization.

192
00:17:04,190 --> 00:17:07,098
Memory, Context & Long-Term Learning.

193
00:17:07,098 --> 00:17:13,168
Understanding how LLMs handle context is crucial for building effective applications.

194
00:17:13,168 --> 00:17:15,536
How Context Windows Really Work:

195
00:17:15,536 --> 00:17:20,139
A context window is the amount of text the model can "see" at once.

196
00:17:20,139 --> 00:17:24,454
Larger windows enable: Processing entire codebases.

197
00:17:24,454 --> 00:17:26,461
Analyzing long documents.

198
00:17:26,461 --> 00:17:28,661
Maintaining longer conversations.

199
00:17:28,661 --> 00:17:33,625
However, larger contexts have trade-offs: Cost scales with context length.

200
00:17:33,625 --> 00:17:35,380
Latency increases.

201
00:17:35,380 --> 00:17:39,995
"Lost in the middle" problem: Models attend less to middle portions.

202
00:17:39,995 --> 00:17:42,892
Quality can degrade for very long contexts.

203
00:17:42,892 --> 00:17:46,834
RAG (Retrieval Augmented Generation) Explained:

204
00:17:46,826 --> 00:17:51,739
RAG solves the context limitation by selectively retrieving relevant information:

205
00:17:51,739 --> 00:17:59,047
Current Limitations of Memory: No true persistent memory across sessions (must be explicitly implemented).

206
00:17:59,047 --> 00:18:03,254
RAG quality depends heavily on chunking and embedding strategy.

207
00:18:03,254 --> 00:18:06,078
Semantic search can miss exact matches.

208
00:18:06,078 --> 00:18:09,648
Cost of storing and querying large knowledge bases.

209
00:18:09,648 --> 00:18:12,388
API Integration & Function Calling.

210
00:18:12,388 --> 00:18:19,107
Modern LLMs are designed to be API-first, enabling deep integration into software systems.

211
00:18:19,107 --> 00:18:24,408
Structured Outputs: Models can generate responses in exact JSON schemas:

212
00:18:24,408 --> 00:18:27,016
Production Patterns for Reliability:

213
00:18:27,016 --> 00:18:30,189
MCP Integration for UPI Payment Status:

214
00:18:30,189 --> 00:18:32,136
Multi-Agent Collaboration.

215
00:18:32,136 --> 00:18:39,492
Beyond single agents, multi-agent systems coordinate specialized AI models to solve complex problems.

216
00:18:39,492 --> 00:18:47,509
What Multi-Agent Systems Are: Instead of one general-purpose agent, you deploy multiple specialized agents that collaborate:

217
00:18:47,509 --> 00:18:51,655
Orchestrator Agent: Breaks down tasks and coordinates others.

218
00:18:51,655 --> 00:18:57,581
Specialist Agents: Handle specific domains (coding, research, analysis).

219
00:18:57,581 --> 00:19:01,391
Reviewer Agents: Validate outputs and catch errors.

