260
00:21:47,881 --> 00:21:51,812
Now let's look at 5 Things Almost Everyone Gets Wrong About AI.

261
00:21:51,812 --> 00:21:56,235
Understanding what AI can't do is as important as knowing what it can.

262
00:21:56,235 --> 00:21:58,675
Here are the most common misconceptions.

263
00:21:58,675 --> 00:22:01,836
1. The Reasoning vs Pattern Matching Debate.

264
00:22:01,836 --> 00:22:09,047
The Misconception: "AI doesn't really reason—it just does sophisticated pattern matching on its training data."

265
00:22:09,047 --> 00:22:13,963
The Reality: This debate is more nuanced than either side admits.

266
00:22:13,963 --> 00:22:19,384
Evidence FOR genuine reasoning: Models solve novel problems not in training data.

267
00:22:19,384 --> 00:22:24,047
Performance improves with "thinking time" (o1, extended thinking).

268
00:22:24,047 --> 00:22:26,355
Models can explain their reasoning steps.

269
00:22:26,355 --> 00:22:30,081
Transfer learning to new domains works surprisingly well.

270
00:22:30,026 --> 00:22:35,432
Evidence AGAINST (or for caution): Failures on seemingly simple logic puzzles.

271
00:22:35,432 --> 00:22:37,896
Sensitivity to problem framing.

272
00:22:37,896 --> 00:22:41,526
Inconsistent performance on isomorphic problems.

273
00:22:41,526 --> 00:22:44,603
Struggles with true out-of-distribution tasks.

274
00:22:44,603 --> 00:22:50,516
What This Means Practically: For most applications, the philosophical question doesn't matter.

275
00:22:50,516 --> 00:22:55,156
What matters is: Can the AI reliably solve your specific problem type?.

276
00:22:55,156 --> 00:22:56,923
Can you verify its outputs?.

277
00:22:56,923 --> 00:22:59,338
Do you have fallback strategies when it fails?.

278
00:22:59,338 --> 00:23:06,394
The practical capability exists regardless of whether we call it "reasoning" or "very sophisticated pattern matching."

279
00:23:06,394 --> 00:23:09,807
2. Emergent Abilities & Scaling Laws.

280
00:23:09,807 --> 00:23:17,427
The Misconception: "AI capabilities are unpredictable—abilities just magically appear at scale."

281
00:23:17,427 --> 00:23:21,466
The Reality: The "emergence" narrative has been partly debunked.

282
00:23:21,466 --> 00:23:27,476
What actually happens: Many "emergent" abilities existed at smaller scales but were hard to measure.

283
00:23:27,476 --> 00:23:34,976
Performance increases smoothly with scale, but our evaluation thresholds create apparent discontinuities.

284
00:23:34,976 --> 00:23:42,031
Some capabilities genuinely do require scale (complex reasoning, nuanced language understanding).

285
00:23:42,031 --> 00:23:48,738
The Scaling Hypothesis: More compute + more data + larger models = better capabilities.

286
00:23:48,738 --> 00:23:55,036
This has held remarkably well since 2020, but: Returns may be diminishing for raw scale.

287
00:23:55,036 --> 00:23:58,161
Quality of training data matters increasingly.

288
00:23:58,161 --> 00:24:01,887
Algorithmic improvements often matter more than size.

289
00:24:01,887 --> 00:24:04,699
Cost scales faster than capability.

290
00:24:04,699 --> 00:24:10,733
For Developers: Don't bet everything on capabilities that require models to get 10x larger.

291
00:24:10,733 --> 00:24:15,913
Focus on what works reliably today and design systems that can upgrade gracefully.

292
00:24:15,913 --> 00:24:18,581
3. The Production vs Demo Gap.

293
00:24:18,581 --> 00:24:24,375
The Misconception: "If the AI can do it in a demo, it can do it reliably in production."

294
00:24:24,375 --> 00:24:28,882
The Reality: There's a massive gap between demo and production performance.

295
00:24:28,882 --> 00:24:30,240
How to Bridge the Gap:

296
00:24:30,240 --> 00:24:34,759
Define success metrics clearly: What does "working" mean for your use case?.

297
00:24:34,759 --> 00:24:39,663
Build evaluation sets: Test on representative samples before deploying.

298
00:24:39,663 --> 00:24:43,930
Implement guardrails: Detect and handle failures gracefully.

299
00:24:43,930 --> 00:24:48,569
Plan for human oversight: Not all decisions should be fully automated.

300
00:24:48,569 --> 00:24:53,317
Start narrow, expand carefully: Begin with constrained use cases.

301
00:24:53,317 --> 00:24:56,875
4. Real vs Perceived Limitations.

302
00:24:56,875 --> 00:25:00,637
What People THINK AI Can't Do: Understand context.

303
00:25:00,637 --> 00:25:01,718
Be creative.

304
00:25:01,718 --> 00:25:03,221
Handle edge cases.

305
00:25:03,221 --> 00:25:04,639
Work with limited data.

306
00:25:04,639 --> 00:25:06,538
Provide consistent answers.

307
00:25:06,538 --> 00:25:12,259
What AI ACTUALLY Struggles With: Reliable factual accuracy (hallucination).

308
00:25:12,259 --> 00:25:15,444
True world state knowledge (no persistent memory).

309
00:25:15,444 --> 00:25:17,968
Real-time information (training cutoffs).

310
00:25:17,968 --> 00:25:20,060
Precise numerical computation.

311
00:25:20,060 --> 00:25:22,932
Physical world interaction without sensors.

312
00:25:22,932 --> 00:25:25,264
Long-term planning under uncertainty.

313
00:25:25,264 --> 00:25:28,846
5. AI Safety & Alignment Progress.

314
00:25:28,846 --> 00:25:33,377
The Misconception: "AI safety is either solved or impossible."

315
00:25:33,377 --> 00:25:38,052
The Reality: Significant progress has been made, but challenges remain.

316
00:25:38,052 --> 00:25:42,367
What's Been Largely Solved: Refusal of clearly harmful requests.

317
00:25:42,367 --> 00:25:45,264
Jailbreak resistance (continuously improving).

318
00:25:45,264 --> 00:25:47,343
Basic instruction following.

319
00:25:47,343 --> 00:25:49,855
Output filtering for illegal content.

320
00:25:49,855 --> 00:25:55,000
What Remains Challenging: Deceptive alignment (AI appearing aligned when it isn't).

321
00:25:55,000 --> 00:25:56,766
Long-horizon goal pursuit.

322
00:25:56,766 --> 00:25:59,098
Value learning from limited feedback.

323
00:25:59,098 --> 00:26:01,718
Handling adversarial users at scale.

324
00:26:01,718 --> 00:26:04,591
Unintended optimization (Goodhart's law).

325
00:26:04,591 --> 00:26:10,853
Indian Perspective on AI Governance: India's AI regulations are still forming.

326
00:26:10,853 --> 00:26:15,949
DPDP Act (2023) covers some AI-adjacent concerns.

327
00:26:15,949 --> 00:26:19,218
No specific AI safety legislation yet.

328
00:26:19,218 --> 00:26:22,812
Industry self-regulation through NASSCOM guidelines.

329
00:26:22,812 --> 00:26:26,286
Growing need for Indian AI ethics frameworks.

330
00:26:26,286 --> 00:26:29,927
For Developers: Follow model provider usage policies.

331
00:26:29,927 --> 00:26:33,209
Implement application-level safety filters.

332
00:26:33,209 --> 00:26:35,228
Log and monitor for misuse.

333
00:26:35,228 --> 00:26:37,812
Stay updated on regulatory changes.

334
00:26:37,812 --> 00:26:41,129
Build with the assumption of adversarial users.

