00:33:28,688 --> 00:33:31,031
Now let's look at Frequently Asked Questions.

437
00:33:31,031 --> 00:33:34,842
What are the real capabilities of AI in 2026?.

438
00:33:34,842 --> 00:34:00,406
AI in 2026 can perform advanced reasoning through chain-of-thought and specialized reasoning models (like o1/o3), use tools and APIs autonomously through function calling and MCP, understand images, documents, and audio with high accuracy, contribute to scientific research including protein structure prediction and mathematical proofs, and coordinate multiple AI agents for complex tasks.

439
00:34:00,406 --> 00:34:04,709
Most users access less than 10% of these capabilities.

440
00:34:04,709 --> 00:34:08,279
Which AI model is best for developers in 2026?.

441
00:34:08,279 --> 00:34:15,719
For most development work, Claude 3.5 Sonnet offers the best balance of capability, reliability, and cost.

442
00:34:15,719 --> 00:34:23,844
For complex reasoning tasks, Claude Opus 4.5 or OpenAI's o1/o3 models excel.

443
00:34:23,844 --> 00:34:31,452
For long-context tasks (large codebases), Gemini 2.0 with its 1M+ token context is ideal.

444
00:34:31,452 --> 00:34:37,329
For budget-conscious projects, Claude Haiku or Llama 3.1 provide good value.

445
00:34:37,329 --> 00:34:39,902
Can AI really do scientific research?.

446
00:34:39,902 --> 00:34:44,325
Yes, AI has made verified contributions to scientific research.

447
00:34:44,325 --> 00:34:50,406
AlphaFold predicted structures for nearly all known proteins, transforming biology.

448
00:34:50,406 --> 00:34:56,993
AlphaProof achieved silver medal performance on International Mathematical Olympiad problems.

449
00:34:56,993 --> 00:35:01,729
AI assists in drug discovery, materials science, and climate modeling.

450
00:35:01,729 --> 00:35:06,140
However, AI augments rather than replaces human researchers.

451
00:35:06,140 --> 00:35:09,373
What is the production vs demo gap in AI?.

452
00:35:09,373 --> 00:35:24,265
The production vs demo gap refers to the difference between AI performance in controlled demonstrations (cherry-picked examples, unlimited retries) versus real-world deployment (varied inputs, reliability requirements, no human curation).

453
00:35:24,265 --> 00:35:31,861
Demo success rates might be 80%, while production reality is often 40-60%.

454
00:35:31,861 --> 00:35:38,567
Bridging this gap requires human-in-the-loop design, robust error handling, and realistic evaluation.

